content:
Your HTML page is well-structured for the task of summing up numbers. However, there are a few improvements you can consider to ensure robustness and usability:

1. **Input Validation:** Ensure that the inputs are valid numbers before performing the calculation. You can use `parseFloat()` instead of `parseInt()` to handle decimal numbers as well.

2. **Handling Empty Inputs:** If any input field is left empty, it should be treated as zero to avoid `NaN` results.

3. **User Feedback:** Provide some feedback or error message if the inputs are invalid.

Here's an improved version of your code:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Sum Calculator</title>
    <style>
        .error {
            color: red;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <form>
        <label for="num1">Number 1:</label>
        <input type="number" id="num1" name="num1"><br><br>
        <label for="num2">Number 2:</label>
        <input type="number" id="num2" name="num2"><br><br>
        <label for="num3">Number 3:</label>
        <input type="number" id="num3" name="num3"><br><br>
        <input type="button" value="Calculate" onclick="calculateSum()"><br><br>
        <label for="result">Result:</label>
        <input type="number" id="result" name="result" readonly><br><br>
        <div id="error-message" class="error"></div>
    </form>
    <script>
        function calculateSum() {
            var num1 = parseFloat(document.getElementById("num1").value) || 0;
            var num2 = parseFloat(document.getElementById("num2").value) || 0;
            var num3 = parseFloat(document.getElementById("num3").value) || 0;

            if (isNaN(num1) || isNaN(num2) || isNaN(num3)) {
                document.getElementById("error-message").innerText = "Please enter valid numbers.";
                document.getElementById("result").value = '';
            } else {
                var result = num1 + num2 + num3;
                document.getElementById("result").value = result;
                document.getElementById("error-message").innerText = '';
            }
        }
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```

### Key Improvements:

- **Using `parseFloat()`**: This allows for decimal input. The `|| 0` ensures that if the input is empty, it defaults to zero.
- **Error Message**: It checks for invalid input and displays an error message if any input is not a number.
- **Styling**: A simple CSS class to highlight error messages.

This code will handle various scenarios, ensuring that users get the correct sum even if they enter decimal numbers or leave some fields empty.
